https://leetcode.com/problems/is-graph-bipartite/description/


QUESTION:
If we are able to colour a graph with two colours such that no adjacent nodes have the same colour, it is called a bipartite graph.
graph = [[1,2,3],[0,2],[0,1,3],[0,2]]
Output: false
SOLUTION:
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
TIME  COMPLEXITY: O(V+E)
SPACE COMPLEXITY: O(V)
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Step 1: you create a color array for visited elements but initialise it to -1;
Step 2: you pass through color[0]==-1 then go though dfs
step 3: [-1 -1 -1 -1]
graph = [[1,2,3],[0,2],[0,1,3],[0,2]]

Start:
color = [-1, -1, -1, -1]

dfs(0, 0)
color = [0, -1, -1, -1]

→ go to 1 -> [0,2]
dfs(1, 1)
color = [0, 1, -1, -1]

→ from 1 go to 2
dfs(2, 0)
color = [0, 1, 0, -1]

→ from 2 check neighbor 0 [0,1,3]
color[2] = 0, color[0] = 0  → SAME COLOR ❌

Return false
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
CODE:
class Solution {
    public boolean dfs(int node,int col,int color[],int graph[][]){
        color[node]=col;
        for(int i:graph[node]){
            if(color[i]==-1){
                if(dfs(i,1-col,color,graph)==false)return false;
            }else if(color[i]==col)return false;
        }
        return true;
    }
    public boolean isBipartite(int[][] graph) {
        int color[]=new int[graph.length];
        for(int i=0;i<graph.length;i++)color[i]=-1;
        for(int i=0;i<graph.length;i++){
            if(color[i]==-1){
                if(dfs(i,0,color,graph)==false)return false;
            }
        }
        return true;
    }
}
